---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/Hero.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import Button from '../../components/Button.astro';
import { clinicInfo } from '../../utils/clinicInfo';
// ✅ ADD THIS IMPORT
import { HERO_IMAGES } from '../../utils/images';

const breadcrumbItems = [
  { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { label: 'Patient Education', href: '/patient-information' },
  { label: 'Tooth Decay', href: '/patient-education/tooth-decay' },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Understanding Tooth Decay | Cavity Prevention | NextGen Dental Austin"
  description="Learn about the causes, prevention, and treatment of tooth decay from the dental experts at NextGen Dental in Austin, TX."
>
  <Hero
    title="Tooth Decay & Cavities"
    subtitle="Prevention is the key to a healthy smile"
    images={[HERO_IMAGES.dental3]} 
    height="md"
  />
  {/* 👆 FIXED: Used HERO_IMAGES.dental3 instead of string path */}

  <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbItems} />

  <div class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 max-w-4xl">
      <article class="prose prose-lg prose-primary mx-auto">
        <h2>What is Tooth Decay?</h2>
        <p>
          Tooth decay (cavities) is the destruction of your tooth enamel, the hard, outer layer of your teeth. It can be a problem for children, teens, and adults. Plaque, a sticky film of bacteria, constantly forms on your teeth. When you eat or drink foods containing sugars, the bacteria in plaque produce acids that attack tooth enamel.
        </p>
        
        <h3>The Process of Decay</h3>
        <p>
          The stickiness of the plaque keeps these acids in contact with your teeth and over time the enamel can break down. This is when cavities can form.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stage 1: White Spots.</strong> Chalky white areas on the surface of the tooth indicate the loss of calcium and buildup of plaque.</li>
          <li><strong>Stage 2: Enamel Decay.</strong> The enamel breaks underneath the tooth's surface.</li>
          <li><strong>Stage 3: Dentin Decay.</strong> If left untreated, bacteria and acids dissolve the enamel and move into the dentin (the softer layer under enamel). Pain usually starts here.</li>
          <li><strong>Stage 4: Pulp Infection.</strong> The decay reaches the pulp (nerve) of the tooth, causing severe pain and infection (abscess).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Prevention</h3>
        <p>
          The good news is that tooth decay is largely preventable.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Brush twice a day with fluoride toothpaste.</li>
          <li>Clean between your teeth daily with floss or interdental cleaners.</li>
          <li>Eat nutritious and balanced meals and limit snacking.</li>
          <li>Check with your dentist about the use of supplemental fluoride.</li>
          <li>Visit {clinicInfo.name} regularly for professional cleanings and oral exams.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="bg-primary-50 p-6 rounded-lg not-prose mt-8 text-center">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Due for a Checkup?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
            Regular exams catch decay early when it's easy to treat.
          </p>
          <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
            <Button 
              href="/contact" 
              text="Book Appointment" 
              variant="primary"
            />
            <Button
              href={`tel:${clinicInfo.phone}`}
              text="Call Us"
              variant="outline"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
